content.text:
Three regimes, three strategies:

| Condition | Problem | Solution |
|---|---|---|
| K < ~32 | K too small to fill vector for VD4DOTS; VREDSUM overhead dominates | Use VQMACC (outer product) — vectorize along N instead |
| (M+N)×K ≤ cache | Everything fits | Direct VD4DOTS (current) — best throughput |
| (M+N)×K > cache | Input/weight thrashing | VD4DOTS **with K-tiling** — tile K to fit cache, use intermediate i32 buffer |

Runtime dispatch at the top of the function:

```c
const long working_set = ((long)lhs_rows + rhs_rows) * rhs_cols;
const long cache_budget = 256 * 1024;  // half of 512KB D-cache

if (rhs_cols < 32) {
    // tiny K — outer product (VQMACC) is better
    nn_mat_mult_vqmacc(...);
} else if (working_set > cache_budget) {
    // large working set — VD4DOTS with K-tiling
    nn_mat_mult_nt_t_s8_v2_tiled(...);
} else {
    // default — direct VD4DOTS
    nn_mat_mult_nt_t_s8_v2(...);
}
```

The middle path (K-tiled VD4DOTS) doesn't exist yet — it would combine VD4DOTS's throughput advantage with tiling's cache discipline. The K-tile size would be chosen so `(M+N) × K_TILE ≤ cache_budget`.

The VQMACC path already exists (baseline code). So the work is:
1. Implement VD4DOTS with K-tiling (new)
2. Add runtime dispatch (straightforward)

Want me to implement this?

